highlights.description: Expresses an immediate reaction to the hearth.  Earlier in the conversation on housing, this was not brought up by Sarah.  So listening to the reality for some Madisonians might have sparked this reaction.

In this case, the hearth sparked a conversation on his direct experience with housing and how complicated it is.  This is an experience I've heard multiple young people (especially, POC) deal with in Madison.

Again, this a direct experience that was shared through a reaction from the hearth.  Which unfortunately is a reality for many including myself.  I spent two weeks in transition (at my parents) from Milwaukee to Madison prior to starting graduate school.  I was lucky my family lived here, but what do others do in that case?
More generally what I hear young folks call their landlords.
Here the hearth snippet reminds Sarah of someone's family who was directly impacted by the development in Madison.  Which could be reflective of growing income inequality right on campus/downtown.
Jesus's reaction to the snippet of the hearth is also reflective of living situations in Madison, especially for young folks whom are living without a family in the city.
Subsidized housing rent has not only increased but is under new leadership.
Highlight emphasizes the troubles of finding housing because apartments downtown are geared towards students, while at the same time landlords downtown abuse student rights.
Highlights how increasing rent is hurting local businesses
Alex describes wanting to demonstrate and engage in activism in Madison, but feared consequences such as jeopardizing family housing.
